06963nam a22007935i 9780822381273DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20012001ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1229160895  a97808223812737 a10.1515/97808223812732doi  a(DE-B1597)554226  a(OCoLC)1058438448  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aGN492b.S75 2001 7aHIS0370002bisacsh00aStates of Imagination :bEthnographic Explorations of the Postcolonial State /ced. by Thomas Blom Hansen, Julia Adams, George Steinmetz, Finn Stepputat. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2001] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (432 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPolitics, History, and Culture : 3000tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: States of Imagination -- tI STATE AND GOVERNANCE -- t‘‘Demonic Societies’’: Liberalism, Biopolitics, and Sovereignty -- tGoverning Population: The Integrated Child Development Services Program in India -- tThe Battlefield and the Prize: ANC’s Bid to Reform the South African State -- tImagining the State as a Space: Territoriality and the Formation of the State in Ecuador -- tII STATE AND JUSTICE -- tThe South African Truth and Reconciliation Commission: A Technique of Nation-State Formation -- tReconstructing National Identity and Renegotiating Memory: The Work of the TRC -- tRethinking Citizenship: Reforming the Law in Postwar Guatemala -- tGovernance and State Mythologies in Mumbai -- tIII STATE AND COMMUNITY -- tBefore History and Prior to Politics: Time, Space, and Territory in the Modern Peruvian Nation-State -- tUrbanizing the Countryside: Armed Conflict, State Formation, and the Politics of Place in Contemporary Guatemala -- tIn the Name of the State? Schools and Teachers in an Andean Province -- tThe Captive State: Corruption, Intelligence Agencies, and Ethnicity in Pakistan -- tPublic Secrets, Conscious Amnesia, and the Celebration of Autonomy for Ladakh -- tBibliography -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe state has recently been rediscovered as an object of inquiry by a broad range of scholars. Reflecting the new vitality of the field of political anthropology, States of Imagination draws together the best of this recent critical thinking to explore the postcolonial state. Contributors focus on a variety of locations from Guatemala, Pakistan, and Peru to India and Ecuador; they study what the state looks like to those seeing it from the vantage points of rural schools, police departments, small villages, and the inside of the Truth and Reconciliation Commission.Focusing on the micropolitics of everyday state-making, the contributors examine the mythologies, paradoxes, and inconsistencies of the state through ethnographies of diverse postcolonial practices. They show how the authority of the state is constantly challenged from the local as well as the global and how growing demands to confer rights and recognition to ever more citizens, organizations, and institutions reveal a persistent myth of the state as a source of social order and an embodiment of popular sovereignty. Demonstrating the indispensable value of ethnographic work on the practices and the symbols of the state, States of Imagination showcases a range of studies and methods to provide insight into the diverse forms of the postcolonial state as an arena of both political and cultural struggle.This collection will interest students and scholars of anthropology, cultural studies, sociology, political science, and history.Contributors. Lars Buur, Mitchell Dean, Akhil Gupta, Thomas Blom Hansen, Steffen Jensen, Aletta J. Norval, David Nugent, Sarah Radcliffe, Rachel Sieder, Finn Stepputat, Martijn van Beek, Oskar Verkaaik, Fiona Wilson  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online res